english:
  title: A Biography of Choe
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Choe Rim passed the Ten-Rhyme Examination in the year of Sinsa. His father, whose name was Seonggо, held the rank of Court Official, and his mother was of the Jang clan, daughter of a certain minister. Choe Rim loved wine and composed poetry, frequenting monasteries in play, departing swiftly from any place where wine was not offered. With a monk named Hanggye he found kindred spirit, and they wandered together constantly. Men of propriety criticized him greatly, yet because his talent shone brilliantly, they gradually showed him respect.

    In the autumn examination of the year Gyesa, I had the fortune of passing alongside Choe. When we gathered for the metropolitan examination at the Central Hall, Choe's eyes grew dim, making it difficult for him to write. He sighed and said: "My former success was mere fortune. Now two men possess greater talent than I. To surpass them and ascend would not be my wish—yet heaven closes my eyes. I shall withdraw." And so he did not sit for the examination.

    Returning to his country, he rose to the rank of Vice Minister of War. In the year Byungsin, bearing credentials to congratulate the capital on the new year, he completed his mission. On the return journey at the Liao River, he encountered bandits. The ambassador, his deputy, and all their retinue were lost. Oh, what tragedy!

    Seok Jungkil of Gizhou was an intimate friend of my father in their youth—a man of vast learning and literary skill, whose students rose to high office and renown. Yet in his old age he still wished to enter the examination halls. When my father became an examiner in the year Jeonghai, Jungkil said: "I studied with Gajeong from childhood. Though fortune might grant me passage, others would surely say he favored me—and I would bring shame upon his name. How could I accept this?" And he withdrew. Though he reached the fifth rank, establishing himself among officials, he retired to discourse with scholars on the classics and histories, never ceasing his labor.

    Choe was his son-in-law. His writing surpassed even Jungkil's art, yet misfortune kept him from advancement, and he died young. Was this the curse of Choe? Or of Jungkil? Jungkil lived long; Choe departed early. Yet in renown, both shall endure to future ages, and perhaps they find solace in that distant place.

    Choe possessed boldness and spoke with resolve. Had death not claimed him, his artistry would have flowered further, rivaling even my humble efforts. Yet his service lasted but briefly, his will unrealized, his writings few, his talents undeveloped. His spirit scattered across the Liao sky, his form hidden in the Liao wilderness. As the crane shall speak at the stone tower and return, so in ages hence shall men read Choe's biography and hear his voice. How can one not grieve?

    Therefore do I set down this account, that it may serve as A Biography of Choe.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gajeong (稼亭) was the sobriquet of Lee Saek's father; the name evokes agricultural virtue and scholarly humility.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to the crane at the stone tower (鶴言華表) alludes to a classical Chinese legend of spiritual transformation and return, suggesting Choe's memory will transcend death.
  - key: ''
    value: The Liao River journey represents an actual historical mission to the Yuan capital; bandits attacking such embassies were a known hazard of the time.
